No bets are in front of me; the action is checked to me on the turn.

Since my hand has no showdown value, it’s a check-fold line unless I decide to bluff. Betting 1/2–2/3 pot (20–30) could get some weaker hands to fold, but it’s rather transparent against a single opponent who has already checked the flop. With only 9♠ blocking hearts (not the A-high flush), a bluff is marginal.

I elect to check back and re-evaluate the river.

[Check]

All the action has checked around, so I am last to act with the betting at 0.

Because I have showdown value with king-high and my only way to beat him is if he has Q-x or worse but it’s very likely he can call given the big stack sizes.

So betting risks more than it gains; checking keeps my showdown equity without investing more.

[Check]
